{"add":{"doc":{"id":"bc761d1442818cba4ffff82e2bdfc6b5d6248934d425199e7d7edd7787d76a77","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/BritishArmyFlag2.svg/200px-BritishArmyFlag2.svg.png","previous":[],"after":["The British Army is the land armed forces branch of the British Armed Forces. It came into being with unification of the governments and armed forces of England and Scotland into the Kingdom of Great Britain in the Acts of Union 1707. The new British Army incorporated regiments that had already existed in England and Scotland and was controlled by the War Office from London. As of 2006, the British Army includes roughly 107,730 active members and 38,460 Territorial Army members. The professional British Army has also been referred to as the Regular Army since the creation of the Territorial Army. The British Army is deployed in many of the world's war zones as part of a fighting force and in United Nations peacekeeping forces."]}}}